The numbers are placed on a regular hexagonal lattice.  
For a cell with axial coordinates \((x,y)\) the six neighbours are obtained by adding the vectors  

\[
(0,-1),\;(-1,0),\;(-1,1),\;(0,1),\;(1,0),\;(1,-1).
\]

---

### 1.  Locate 2026 on the lattice  

For a hexagonal “spiral’’ the numbers that lie on the same ring have the same
maximum‑coordinate  

\[
k=\max\{|x|,\;|y|,\;| -x-y|\}.
\]

The greatest number that lies on ring \(k\) is  

\[
M(k)=1+3k(k+1)
\]

and the smallest number on that ring is  

\[
S(k)=M(k-1)+1 = 3k(k-1)+2 .
\]

Since  

\[
M(25)=1+3\cdot25\cdot26 = 1951,\qquad  
M(26)=1+3\cdot26\cdot27 = 2107 ,
\]

the integer \(2026\) is on ring \(k=26\).

Its offset inside the ring is  

\[
m = 2026-S(26)=2026-1952=74 .
\]

Walking from the start of the ring (the cell \((26,0)\) we move  

* \(k\) steps in direction \((0,-1)\) (side 0)  
* another \(k\) steps in direction \((-1,0)\) (side 1)  
* then the remaining \(m-2k=22\) steps on side 2 whose direction is \((-1,1)\).

Hence the coordinate of 2026 is  

\[
(26,0) + 26(0,-1)+26(-1,0)+22(-1,1)=(-22,-4).
\]

---

### 2.  Coordinates of the six neighbours  

\[
\begin{aligned}
(-22,-5),\;&(-23,-4),\;(-23,-3),\\
(-22,-3),\;&(-21,-4),\;(-21,-5).
\end{aligned}
\]

---

### 3.  Number that sits at a given coordinate  

For a coordinate \((x,y)\) let  

\[
k=\max\{|x|,|y|,| -x-y|\}.
\]

If \(k=0\) the number is 1.  
Otherwise the walk that produces the ring begins at \((k,0)\) (the number \(S(k)=3k(k-1)+2\)).
Let the six sides be numbered 0 … 5 with the direction vectors  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{d}_0&=(0,-1),\\
\mathbf{d}_1&=(-1,0),\\
\mathbf{d}_2&=(-1,1),\\
\mathbf{d}_3&=(0,1),\\
\mathbf{d}_4&=(1,0),\\
\mathbf{d}_5&=(1,-1).
\end{aligned}
\]

If the point lies on side 0 we have \(x=k\) and \(-k<y\le 0\); on side 1 we have \(y=-k\); on side 2 we have \(x=-k\); on side 3 we have \(y=k\); on side 4 we have \(x=k\); on side 5 we have \(x+y=0\).

The offset \(t\) (starting from 0) is

\[
t=\begin{cases}
k-y-1                     &\text{side 0}\\[2pt]
k+(k-x-1)                &\text{side 1}\\[2pt]
2k+(y+k-1)               &\text{side 2}\\[2pt]
3k+(x+k-1)               &\text{side 3}\\[2pt]
4k+(x-k-1)               &\text{side 4}\\[2pt]
5k+( -x-y-1)               &\text{side 5}
\end{cases}
\]

The number in the cell is  

\[
N(x,y)=S(k)+t .
\]

---

### 4.  Apply it to the six neighbour coordinates  

| coordinate | \(k\) | side | offset \(t\) | number \(N\) |
|-----------|------|------|--------------|--------------|
| \((-22,-5)\) | 22 | 2 | \(2\! \times\!22+( -5+22-1)=60\) | \(1388+60 = 1448\) |
| \((-23,-4)\) | 23 | 2 | \(2\! \times\!23+( -4+23-1)=64\) | \(1520+64 = 1584\) |
| \((-23,-3)\) | 23 | 2 | \(2\! \times\!23+( -3+23-1)=65\) | \(1520+65 = 1585\) |
| \((-22,-3)\) | 22 | 2 | \(44+( -3+22-1)=62\) | \(1388+62 = 1450\) |
| \((-21,-4)\) | 21 | 2 | \(42+( -4+21-1)=58\) | \(1262+58 = 1320\) |
| \((-21,-5)\) | 21 | 2 | \(42+( -5+21-1)=57\) | \(1262+57 = 1319\) |

---

### 5.  Sum of the six neighbours  

\[
1448+1584+1585+1450+1320+1319 = 8706 .
\]

\[
\boxed{8706}
\]
